ecs_task_execution.cluster: (Required) Short name or full Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the cluster to run the task on.
ecs_task_execution.task_definition:
(Required) The `family` and `revision` (`family:revision`) or full ARN of the task definition to run. If a revision isn't specified, the latest `ACTIVE` revision is used.

The following arguments are optional:

capacity_provider_strategy.base: (Optional) The number of tasks, at a minimum, to run on the specified capacity provider. Only one capacity provider in a capacity provider strategy can have a base defined. Defaults to `0`.
capacity_provider_strategy.weight: (Optional) The relative percentage of the total number of launched tasks that should use the specified capacity provider. The `weight` value is taken into consideration after the `base` count of tasks has been satisfied. Defaults to `0`.

ecs_task_execution.desired_count: (Optional) Number of instantiations of the specified task to place on your cluster. You can specify up to 10 tasks for each call.
ecs_task_execution.enable_ecs_managed_tags: (Optional) Specifies whether to enable Amazon ECS managed tags for the tasks within the service.
ecs_task_execution.enable_execute_command: (Optional) Specifies whether to enable Amazon ECS Exec for the tasks within the service.
ecs_task_execution.group: (Optional) Name of the task group to associate with the task. The default value is the family name of the task definition.
ecs_task_execution.launch_type: (Optional) Launch type on which to run your service. Valid values are `EC2`, `FARGATE`, and `EXTERNAL`.

network_configuration.subnets: (Required) Subnets associated with the task or service.
network_configuration.security_groups: (Optional) Security groups associated with the task or service. If you do not specify a security group, the default security group for the VPC is used.
network_configuration.assign_public_ip:
(Optional) Assign a public IP address to the ENI (Fargate launch type only). Valid values are `true` or `false`. Default `false`.

For more information, see the [Task Networking](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task-networking.html) documentation.

overrides.container_overrides: (Optional) One or more container overrides that are sent to a task. See below.
overrides.cpu: (Optional) The CPU override for the task.
overrides.execution_role_arn: (Optional) Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the task execution role override for the task.
overrides.inference_accelerator_overrides: (Optional) Elastic Inference accelerator override for the task. See below.
overrides.memory: (Optional) The memory override for the task.
overrides.task_role_arn: (Optional) Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the role that containers in this task can assume.

placement_constraints.expression: (Optional) A cluster query language expression to apply to the constraint. The expression can have a maximum length of 2000 characters. You can't specify an expression if the constraint type is `distinctInstance`.
placement_constraints.type: (Optional) The type of constraint. Valid values are `distinctInstance` or `memberOf`. Use `distinctInstance` to ensure that each task in a particular group is running on a different container instance. Use `memberOf` to restrict the selection to a group of valid candidates.

placement_strategy.field: (Optional) The field to apply the placement strategy against.
placement_strategy.type:
(Optional) The type of placement strategy. Valid values are `random`, `spread`, and `binpack`.

For more information, see the [Placement Strategy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/APIReference/API_PlacementStrategy.html) documentation.

ecs_task_execution.platform_version: (Optional) The platform version the task uses. A platform version is only specified for tasks hosted on Fargate. If one isn't specified, the `LATEST` platform version is used.
ecs_task_execution.propagate_tags: (Optional) Specifies whether to propagate the tags from the task definition to the task. If no value is specified, the tags aren't propagated. An error will be received if you specify the `SERVICE` option when running a task. Valid values are `TASK_DEFINITION` or `NONE`.
ecs_task_execution.reference_id: (Optional) The reference ID to use for the task.
ecs_task_execution.started_by: (Optional) An optional tag specified when a task is started.
ecs_task_execution.tags: (Optional) Key-value map of resource tags. If configured with a provider [`default_tags` configuration block](https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest/docs#default_tags-configuration-block) present, tags with matching keys will overwrite those defined at the provider-level.

container_overrides.command: (Optional) The command to send to the container that overrides the default command from the Docker image or the task definition.
container_overrides.cpu: (Optional) The number of cpu units reserved for the container, instead of the default value from the task definition.
container_overrides.environment: (Optional) The environment variables to send to the container. You can add new environment variables, which are added to the container at launch, or you can override the existing environment variables from the Docker image or the task definition. See below.
container_overrides.memory: (Optional) The hard limit (in MiB) of memory to present to the container, instead of the default value from the task definition. If your container attempts to exceed the memory specified here, the container is killed.
container_overrides.memory_reservation: (Optional) The soft limit (in MiB) of memory to reserve for the container, instead of the default value from the task definition.
container_overrides.name: (Optional) The name of the container that receives the override. This parameter is required if any override is specified.
container_overrides.resource_requirements: (Optional) The type and amount of a resource to assign to a container, instead of the default value from the task definition. The only supported resource is a GPU. See below.

inference_accelerator_overrides.device_name: (Optional) The Elastic Inference accelerator device name to override for the task. This parameter must match a deviceName specified in the task definition.
inference_accelerator_overrides.device_type: (Optional) The Elastic Inference accelerator type to use.

environment.key: (Required) The name of the key-value pair. For environment variables, this is the name of the environment variable.
environment.value: (Required) The value of the key-value pair. For environment variables, this is the value of the environment variable.

resource_requirements.type: (Required) The type of resource to assign to a container. Valid values are `GPU` or `InferenceAccelerator`.
resource_requirements.value: (Required) The value for the specified resource type. If the `GPU` type is used, the value is the number of physical GPUs the Amazon ECS container agent reserves for the container. The number of GPUs that's reserved for all containers in a task can't exceed the number of available GPUs on the container instance that the task is launched on. If the `InferenceAccelerator` type is used, the value matches the `deviceName` for an InferenceAccelerator specified in a task definition.

ecs_task_execution.task_arns: (Output Only) A list of the provisioned task ARNs.
ecs_task_execution.id: (Output Only) The unique identifier, which is a comma-delimited string joining the `cluster` and `task_definition` attributes.

ami_ids.owners: (Required) List of AMI owners to limit search. At least 1 value must be specified. Valid values: an AWS account ID, `self` (the current account), or an AWS owner alias (e.g., `amazon`, `aws-marketplace`, `microsoft`).
ami_ids.executable_users:
(Optional) Limit search to users with explicit launch
permission on  the image. Valid items are the numeric account ID or `self`.
ami_ids.filter:
(Optional) One or more name/value pairs to filter off of. There
are several valid keys, for a full reference, check out
[describe-images in the AWS CLI reference][1].
ami_ids.name_regex:
(Optional) Regex string to apply to the AMI list returned
by AWS. This allows more advanced filtering not supported from the AWS API.
This filtering is done locally on what AWS returns, and could have a performance
impact if the result is large. Combine this with other
options to narrow down the list AWS returns.
ami_ids.sort_ascending:
(Optional) Used to sort AMIs by creation time.
If no value is specified, the default value is `false`.
ami_ids.include_deprecated:
(Optional) If true, all deprecated AMIs are included in the response.
If false, no deprecated AMIs are included in the response. If no value is specified, the default value is `false`.

endpoint.id: (Required) ID of an endpoint you want to assign.
endpoint.type: (Optional) Type of the endpoint. Valid values are `value` , `cloudfront` , `elastic-load-balancer`, `s3-website`
endpoint.region: (Optional) To route traffic to an Amazon S3 bucket that is configured as a website endpoint, specify the region in which you created the bucket for `region`.

route53_traffic_policy_document.record_type: (Optional) DNS type of all of the resource record sets that Amazon Route 53 will create based on this traffic policy.

rule.id: (Required) ID of a rule you want to assign.
rule.primary: (Optional) Configuration block for the settings for the rule or endpoint that you want to route traffic to whenever the corresponding resources are available. Only valid for `failover` type. See below
rule.secondary: (Optional) Configuration block for the rule or endpoint that you want to route traffic to whenever the primary resources are not available. Only valid for `failover` type. See below
rule.location: (Optional) Configuration block for when you add a geolocation rule, you configure your traffic policy to route your traffic based on the geographic location of your users.  Only valid for `geo` type. See below
rule.geo_proximity_location: (Optional) Configuration block for when you add a geoproximity rule, you configure Amazon Route 53 to route traffic to your resources based on the geographic location of your resources. Only valid for `geoproximity` type. See below
rule.regions: (Optional) Configuration block for when you add a latency rule, you configure your traffic policy to route your traffic based on the latency (the time delay) between your users and the AWS regions where you've created AWS resources such as ELB load balancers and Amazon S3 buckets. Only valid for `latency` type. See below
rule.items: (Optional) Configuration block for when you add a multivalue answer rule, you configure your traffic policy to route traffic approximately randomly to your healthy resources.  Only valid for `multivalue` type. See below

route53_traffic_policy_document.start_endpoint: (Optional) An endpoint to be as the starting point for the traffic policy.
route53_traffic_policy_document.start_rule: (Optional) A rule to be as the starting point for the traffic policy.
route53_traffic_policy_document.version: (Optional) Version of the traffic policy format.

region.evaluate_target_health: (Optional) Indicates whether you want Amazon Route 53 to evaluate the health of the endpoint and route traffic only to healthy endpoints.
region.health_check: (Optional) If you want to associate a health check with the endpoint or rule.
region.region: (Optional) Region code for the AWS Region that you created the resource in.

primary.evaluate_target_health: (Optional) Indicates whether you want Amazon Route 53 to evaluate the health of the endpoint and route traffic only to healthy endpoints.
primary.health_check: (Optional) If you want to associate a health check with the endpoint or rule.

location.evaluate_target_health: (Optional) Indicates whether you want Amazon Route 53 to evaluate the health of the endpoint and route traffic only to healthy endpoints.
location.health_check: (Optional) If you want to associate a health check with the endpoint or rule.
location.is_default: (Optional) Indicates whether this set of values represents the default location.

geo_proximity_location.bias: (Optional) Specify a value for `bias` if you want to route more traffic to an endpoint from nearby endpoints (positive values) or route less traffic to an endpoint (negative values).
geo_proximity_location.evaluate_target_health: (Optional) Indicates whether you want Amazon Route 53 to evaluate the health of the endpoint and route traffic only to healthy endpoints.
geo_proximity_location.health_check: (Optional) If you want to associate a health check with the endpoint or rule.
geo_proximity_location.latitude: (Optional) Represents the location south (negative) or north (positive) of the equator. Valid values are -90 degrees to 90 degrees.
geo_proximity_location.longitude: (Optional) Represents the location west (negative) or east (positive) of the prime meridian. Valid values are -180 degrees to 180 degrees.
geo_proximity_location.region: (Optional) If your endpoint is an AWS resource, specify the AWS Region that you created the resource in.

dms_replication_task.replication_task_id:
(Required) The replication task identifier.

    - Must contain from 1 to 255 alphanumeric characters or hyphens.
    - First character must be a letter.
    - Cannot end with a hyphen.
    - Cannot contain two consecutive hyphens.
dms_replication_task.cdc_start_position: (Output Only) (Conflicts with `cdc_start_time`) Indicates when you want a change data capture (CDC) operation to start. The value can be in date, checkpoint, or LSN/SCN format depending on the source engine. For more information, see [Determining a CDC native start point](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/dms/latest/userguide/CHAP_Task.CDC.html#CHAP_Task.CDC.StartPoint.Native).
dms_replication_task.cdc_start_time: (Output Only) (Conflicts with `cdc_start_position`) The Unix timestamp integer for the start of the Change Data Capture (CDC) operation.
dms_replication_task.migration_type: (Output Only) The migration type. Can be one of `full-load | cdc | full-load-and-cdc`.
dms_replication_task.replication_instance_arn: (Output Only) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the replication instance.
dms_replication_task.replication_task_settings: (Output Only) An escaped JSON string that contains the task settings. For a complete list of task settings, see [Task Settings for AWS Database Migration Service Tasks](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/dms/latest/userguide/CHAP_Tasks.CustomizingTasks.TaskSettings.html).
dms_replication_task.source_endpoint_arn: (Output Only) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) string that uniquely identifies the source endpoint.
dms_replication_task.start_replication_task: (Output Only) Whether to run or stop the replication task.
dms_replication_task.table_mappings: (Output Only) An escaped JSON string that contains the table mappings. For information on table mapping see [Using Table Mapping with an AWS Database Migration Service Task to Select and Filter Data](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/dms/latest/userguide/CHAP_Tasks.CustomizingTasks.TableMapping.html)
dms_replication_task.target_endpoint_arn: (Output Only) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) string that uniquely identifies the target endpoint.
dms_replication_task.replication_task_arn: (Output Only) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) for the replication task.

Each row in the table represents a word or a phrase, described with Phrase, IPA, SoundsLike, and DisplayAs fields. Separate the fields with TAB characters. Valid Values are `ar-AE`, `de-CH`, `de-DE`, `en-AB`, `en-AU`, `en-GB`, `en-IE`, `en-IN`, `en-US`, `en-WL`, `es-ES`, `es-US`, `fr-CA`, `fr-FR`, `hi-IN`, `it-IT`, `ja-JP`, `ko-KR`, `pt-BR`, `pt-PT`, `zh-CN`.

cloudfront_realtime_log_config.name: (Required) Unique name to identify this real-time log configuration.

cloudfront_realtime_log_config.fields: (Output Only) (Required) Fields that are included in each real-time log record. See the [AWS documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/real-time-logs.html#understand-real-time-log-config-fields) for supported values.
cloudfront_realtime_log_config.sampling_rate:
(Output Only) (Required) Sampling rate for this real-time log configuration. The sampling rate determines the percentage of viewer requests that are represented in the real-time log data. An integer between `1` and `100`, inclusive.

The `endpoint` object supports the following:
cloudfront_realtime_log_config.kinesis_stream_config: (Output Only) (Required) Amazon Kinesis data stream configuration.
cloudfront_realtime_log_config.stream_type:
(Output Only) (Required) Type of data stream where real-time log data is sent. The only valid value is `Kinesis`.

The `kinesis_stream_config` object supports the following:
cloudfront_realtime_log_config.role_arn:
(Output Only) (Required) ARN of an [IAM role](iam_role.html) that CloudFront can use to send real-time log data to the Kinesis data stream.
See the [AWS documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/real-time-logs.html#understand-real-time-log-config-iam-role) for more information.
cloudfront_realtime_log_config.stream_arn: (Output Only) (Required) ARN of the [Kinesis data stream](kinesis_stream.html).

Please refer to the [S3 endpoints reference](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/general/latest/gr/s3.html#s3_region) for format. Note: AWS CloudFront allows specifying an S3 region-specific endpoint when creating an S3 origin. This will prevent redirect issues from CloudFront to the S3 Origin URL. For more information, see the [Virtual Hosted-Style Requests for Other Regions](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/VirtualHosting.html#deprecated-global-endpoint) section in the AWS S3 User Guide.

(Optional) Set this value to true to include manual DB snapshots that are public and can be
copied or restored by any AWS account, otherwise set this value to false. The default is `false`.

iam_principal_policy_simulation.action_names:
(Required) A set of IAM action names to run simulations for. Each entry in this set adds an additional hypothetical request to the simulation.

    Action names consist of a service prefix and an action verb separated by a colon, such as `s3:GetObject`. Refer to [Actions, resources, and condition keys for AWS services](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/service-authorization/latest/reference/reference_policies_actions-resources-contextkeys.html) to see the full set of possible IAM action names across all AWS services.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.policy_source_arn:
(Required) The [ARN](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/general/latest/gr/aws-arns-and-namespaces.html) of the IAM user, group, or role whose policies will be included in the simulation.

You must closely match the form of the real service request you are simulating in order to achieve a realistic result. You can use the following additional arguments to specify other characteristics of the simulated requests:
iam_principal_policy_simulation.caller_arn: (Optional) The ARN of an user that will appear as the "caller" of the simulated requests. If you do not specify `caller_arn` then the simulation will use the `policy_source_arn` instead, if it contains a user ARN.

context.key:
(Required) The context _condition key_ to set.

    If you have policies containing `Condition` elements or using dynamic interpolations then you will need to provide suitable values for each condition key your policies use. See [Actions, resources, and condition keys for AWS services](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/service-authorization/latest/reference/reference_policies_actions-resources-contextkeys.html) to find the various condition keys that are normally provided for real requests to each action of each AWS service.
context.type:
(Required) An IAM value type that determines how the policy simulator will interpret the strings given in `values`.

    For more information, see the `ContextKeyType` field of [`iam.ContextEntry`](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/APIReference/API_ContextEntry.html) in the underlying API.
context.values: (Required) A set of one or more values for this context entry.

iam_principal_policy_simulation.additional_policies_json: (Optional) A set of additional principal policy documents to include in the simulation. The simulator will behave as if each of these policies were associated with the object specified in `policy_source_arn`, allowing you to test the effect of hypothetical policies not yet created.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.permissions_boundary_policies_json: (Optional) A set of [permissions boundary policy documents](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies_boundaries.html) to include in the simulation.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.resource_arns:
(Optional) A set of ARNs of resources to include in the simulation.

    This argument is important for actions that have either required or optional resource types listed in [Actions, resources, and condition keys for AWS services](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/service-authorization/latest/reference/reference_policies_actions-resources-contextkeys.html), and you must provide ARNs that identify AWS objects of the appropriate types for the chosen actions.

    The policy simulator only automatically loads policies associated with the `policy_source_arn`, so if your given resources have their own resource-level policy then you'll also need to provide that explicitly using the `resource_policy_json` argument to achieve a realistic simulation.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.resource_handling_option:
(Optional) Specifies a special simulation type to run. Some EC2 actions require special simulation behaviors and a particular set of resource ARNs to achieve a realistic result.

    For more details, see the `ResourceHandlingOption` request parameter for [the underlying `iam:SimulatePrincipalPolicy` action](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/APIReference/API_SimulatePrincipalPolicy.html).
iam_principal_policy_simulation.resource_owner_account_id: (Optional) An AWS account ID to use for any resource ARN in `resource_arns` that doesn't include its own AWS account ID. If unspecified, the simulator will use the account ID from the `caller_arn` argument as a placeholder.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.resource_policy_json:
(Optional) An IAM policy document representing the resource-level policy of all of the resources specified in `resource_arns`.

    The policy simulator cannot automatically load policies that are associated with individual resources, as described in the documentation for `resource_arns` above.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.all_allowed:
(Output Only) `true` if all of the simulation results have decision "allowed", or `false` otherwise.

    This is a convenient shorthand for the common case of requiring that all of the simulated requests passed in a postcondition associated with the data source. If you need to describe a more granular condition, use the `results` attribute instead.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.results: (Output Only) A set of result objects, one for each of the simulated requests, with the following nested attributes:
iam_principal_policy_simulation.action_name: (Output Only) The name of the single IAM action used for this particular request.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.decision: (Output Only) The raw decision determined from all of the policies in scope; either "allowed", "explicitDeny", or "implicitDeny".
iam_principal_policy_simulation.decision_details: (Output Only) A map of arbitrary metadata entries returned by the policy simulator for this request.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.resource_arn: (Output Only) ARN of the resource that was used for this particular request. When you specify multiple actions and multiple resource ARNs, that causes a separate policy request for each combination of unique action and resource.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.matched_statements: (Output Only) A nested set of objects describing which policies contained statements that were relevant to this simulation request. Each object has attributes `source_policy_id` and `source_policy_type` to identify one of the policies.
iam_principal_policy_simulation.missing_context_keys: (Output Only) A set of context keys (or condition keys) that were needed by some of the policies contributing to this result but not specified using a `context` block in the configuration. Missing or incorrect context keys will typically cause a simulated request to be disallowed.

organizations_organization.non_master_accounts: (Output Only) List of organization accounts excluding the master account. For a list including the master account, see the `accounts` attribute. All elements have these attributes:

api_gateway_rest_api.api_key_source: (Output Only) Source of the API key for requests.

api_gateway_rest_api.binary_media_types: (Output Only) List of binary media types supported by the REST API.

api_gateway_rest_api.endpoint_configuration: (Output Only) The endpoint configuration of this RestApi showing the endpoint types of the API.
api_gateway_rest_api.execution_arn: (Output Only) Execution ARN part to be used in [`lambda_permission`](/docs/providers/aws/r/lambda_permission.html)'s `source_arn` when allowing API Gateway to invoke a Lambda function, e.g., `arn:aws:execute-api:eu-west-2:123456789012:z4675bid1j`, which can be concatenated with allowed stage, method and resource path.
api_gateway_rest_api.id: (Output Only) Set to the ID of the found REST API.
api_gateway_rest_api.minimum_compression_size: (Output Only) Minimum response size to compress for the REST API.
api_gateway_rest_api.policy: (Output Only) JSON formatted policy document that controls access to the API Gateway.
api_gateway_rest_api.root_resource_id: (Output Only) Set to the ID of the API Gateway Resource on the found REST API where the route matches '/'.

filter.name: (Required) Name of the field to filter by, as defined by [the underlying AWS API](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/fsx/latest/APIReference/API_StorageVirtualMachineFilter.html).
filter.values: (Required) Set of values that are accepted for the given field. An SVM will be selected if any one of the given values matches.

ami.owners: (Optional) List of AMI owners to limit search. Valid values: an AWS account ID, `self` (the current account), or an AWS owner alias (e.g., `amazon`, `aws-marketplace`, `microsoft`).
ami.most_recent:
(Optional) If more than one result is returned, use the most
recent AMI.
ami.executable_users:
(Optional) Limit search to users with explicit launch permission on
 the image. Valid items are the numeric account ID or `self`.
ami.include_deprecated: (Optional) If true, all deprecated AMIs are included in the response. If false, no deprecated AMIs are included in the response. If no value is specified, the default value is false.
ami.filter:
(Optional) One or more name/value pairs to filter off of. There are
several valid keys, for a full reference, check out
[describe-images in the AWS CLI reference][1].
ami.name_regex:
(Optional) Regex string to apply to the AMI list returned
by AWS. This allows more advanced filtering not supported from the AWS API. This
filtering is done locally on what AWS returns, and could have a performance
impact if the result is large. Combine this with other
options to narrow down the list AWS returns.

~> NOTE: If more or less than a single match is returned by the search,
Terraform will fail. Ensure that your search is specific enough to return
a single AMI ID only, or use `most_recent` to choose the most recent one. If
you want to match multiple AMIs, use the `aws_ami_ids` data source instead.
ami.architecture: (Output Only) OS architecture of the AMI (ie: `i386` or `x86_64`).
ami.boot_mode: (Output Only) Boot mode of the image.
ami.block_device_mappings: (Output Only) Set of objects with block device mappings of the AMI.
ami.device_name: (Output Only) Physical name of the device.
ami.ebs: (Output Only) Map containing EBS information, if the device is EBS based. Unlike most object attributes, these are accessed directly (e.g., `ebs.volume_size` or `ebs["volume_size"]`) rather than accessed through the first element of a list (e.g., `ebs[0].volume_size`).
ami.delete_on_termination: (Output Only) `true` if the EBS volume will be deleted on termination.
ami.encrypted: (Output Only) `true` if the EBS volume is encrypted.
ami.iops: (Output Only) `0` if the EBS volume is not a provisioned IOPS image, otherwise the supported IOPS count.
ami.snapshot_id: (Output Only) The ID of the snapshot.
ami.volume_size: (Output Only) The size of the volume, in GiB.
ami.throughput: (Output Only) The throughput that the EBS volume supports, in MiB/s.
ami.no_device: (Output Only) Suppresses the specified device included in the block device mapping of the AMI.
ami.virtual_name: (Output Only) Virtual device name (for instance stores).
ami.creation_date: (Output Only) Date and time the image was created.
ami.deprecation_time: (Output Only) Date and time when the image will be deprecated.
ami.description:
(Output Only) Description of the AMI that was provided during image
  creation.
ami.hypervisor: (Output Only) Hypervisor type of the image.
ami.image_id: (Output Only) ID of the AMI. Should be the same as the resource `id`.
ami.image_owner_alias:
(Output Only) AWS account alias (for example, `amazon`, `self`) or
  the AWS account ID of the AMI owner.
ami.imds_support: (Output Only) Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) support mode for the image. Set to `v2.0` if instances ran from this image enforce IMDSv2.
ami.kernel_id:
(Output Only) Kernel associated with the image, if any. Only applicable
  for machine images.
ami.name: (Output Only) Name of the AMI that was provided during image creation.
ami.owner_id: (Output Only) AWS account ID of the image owner.
ami.platform: (Output Only) Value is Windows for `Windows` AMIs; otherwise blank.
ami.product_codes: (Output Only) Any product codes associated with the AMI.
ami.public: (Output Only) `true` if the image has public launch permissions.
ami.ramdisk_id:
(Output Only) RAM disk associated with the image, if any. Only applicable
  for machine images.
ami.root_device_name: (Output Only) Device name of the root device.
ami.root_device_type: (Output Only) Type of root device (ie: `ebs` or `instance-store`).
ami.root_snapshot_id:
(Output Only) Snapshot id associated with the root device, if any
  (only applies to `ebs` root devices).
ami.sriov_net_support: (Output Only) Whether enhanced networking is enabled.
ami.state:
(Output Only) Current state of the AMI. If the state is `available`, the image
  is successfully registered and can be used to launch an instance.
ami.state_reason: (Output Only) Describes a state change. Fields are `UNSET` if not available.
ami.tags: (Output Only) Any tags assigned to the image.
ami.tpm_support: (Output Only) If the image is configured for NitroTPM support, the value is `v2.0`.
ami.virtualization_type:
(Output Only) Type of virtualization of the AMI (ie: `hvm` or
  `paravirtual`).
ami.usage_operation: (Output Only) Operation of the Amazon EC2 instance and the billing code that is associated with the AMI.
ami.platform_details: (Output Only) Platform details associated with the billing code of the AMI.
ami.ena_support: (Output Only) Whether enhanced networking with ENA is enabled.

(Output Only) The key-value pair used to resolve dynamic parameter values when processing a Systems Manager Automation runbook.

It includes the expiry-date and rule-id key value pairs providing object expiration information. The value of the rule-id is URL encoded.

(Output Only) - Map of tags assigned to the object.

-> Note: Terraform ignores all leading `/`s in the object's `key` and treats multiple `/`s in the rest of the object's `key` as a single `/`, so values of `/index.html` and `index.html` correspond to the same S3 object as do `first//second///third//` and `first/second/third/`.

budgets_budget.name:
The name of a budget. Unique within accounts.

The following arguments are optional:
budgets_budget.account_id: The ID of the target account for budget. Will use current user's account_id by default if omitted.
budgets_budget.name_prefix: The prefix of the name of a budget. Unique within accounts.

auto_adjust_data.auto_adjust_type: (Output Only) (Required) The string that defines whether your budget auto-adjusts based on historical or forecasted data. Valid values: `FORECAST`,`HISTORICAL`.

historical_options.budget_adjustment_period: (Output Only) (Required) The number of budget periods included in the moving-average calculation that determines your auto-adjusted budget amount.
historical_options.lookback_available_periods: (Output Only) (Optional) The integer that describes how many budget periods in your BudgetAdjustmentPeriod are included in the calculation of your current budget limit. If the first budget period in your BudgetAdjustmentPeriod has no cost data, then that budget period isnt included in the average that determines your budget limit. You cant set your own LookBackAvailablePeriods. The value is automatically calculated from the `budget_adjustment_period` and your historical cost data.

auto_adjust_data.last_auto_adjust_time: (Output Only) (Optional) The last time that your budget was auto-adjusted.

budgets_budget.budget_exceeded: (Output Only) Boolean indicating whether this budget has been exceeded.
budgets_budget.budget_limit: (Output Only) The total amount of cost, usage, RI utilization, RI coverage, Savings Plans utilization, or Savings Plans coverage that you want to track with your budget. Contains object [Spend](#spend).
budgets_budget.budget_type: (Output Only) Whether this budget tracks monetary cost or usage.
budgets_budget.calculated_spend: (Output Only) The spend objects that are associated with this budget. The [actualSpend](#actual-spend) tracks how much you've used, cost, usage, RI units, or Savings Plans units and the [forecastedSpend](#forecasted-spend) tracks how much that you're predicted to spend based on your historical usage profile.

cost_filter.instancetype: (Output Only) Refer to [AWS CostFilter documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cost-management/latest/userguide/budgets-create-filters.html) for further detail.

cost_types.include_credit: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include credits in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_discount: (Output Only) Whether a budget includes discounts. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_other_subscription: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include other subscription costs in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_recurring: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include recurring costs in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_refund: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include refunds in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_subscription: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include subscriptions in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_support: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include support costs in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_tax: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include tax in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.include_upfront: (Output Only) A boolean value whether to include upfront costs in the cost budget. Defaults to `true`.
cost_types.use_amortized: (Output Only) Whether a budget uses the amortized rate. Defaults to `false`.
cost_types.use_blended:
(Output Only) A boolean value whether to use blended costs in the cost budget. Defaults to `false`.

Refer to [AWS CostTypes documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-cost-management/latest/APIReference/API_budgets_CostTypes.html) for further detail.

budgets_budget.notification: (Output Only) Object containing [Budget Notifications](#budget-notification). Can be used multiple times to define more than one budget notification.
budgets_budget.planned_limit: (Output Only) Object containing [Planned Budget Limits](#planned-budget-limits). Can be used multiple times to plan more than one budget limit. See [PlannedBudgetLimits](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-cost-management/latest/APIReference/API_budgets_Budget.html#awscostmanagement-Type-budgets_Budget-PlannedBudgetLimits) documentation.
budgets_budget.time_period_end: (Output Only) The end of the time period covered by the budget. There are no restrictions on the end date. Format: `2017-01-01_12:00`.
budgets_budget.time_period_start: (Output Only) The start of the time period covered by the budget. If you don't specify a start date, AWS defaults to the start of your chosen time period. The start date must come before the end date. Format: `2017-01-01_12:00`.
budgets_budget.time_unit: (Output Only) The length of time until a budget resets the actual and forecasted spend. Valid values: `MONTHLY`, `QUARTERLY`, `ANNUALLY`, and `DAILY`.
budgets_budget.comparison_operator: (Output Only) (Required) Comparison operator to use to evaluate the condition. Can be `LESS_THAN`, `EQUAL_TO` or `GREATER_THAN`.
budgets_budget.threshold: (Output Only) (Required) Threshold when the notification should be sent.
budgets_budget.threshold_type: (Output Only) (Required) What kind of threshold is defined. Can be `PERCENTAGE` OR `ABSOLUTE_VALUE`.
budgets_budget.notification_type: (Output Only) (Required) What kind of budget value to notify on. Can be `ACTUAL` or `FORECASTED`.
budgets_budget.subscriber_email_addresses: (Output Only) (Optional) E-Mail addresses to notify. Either this or `subscriber_sns_topic_arns` is required.
budgets_budget.subscriber_sns_topic_arns: (Output Only) (Optional) SNS topics to notify. Either this or `subscriber_email_addresses` is required.
budgets_budget.amount: (Output Only) The cost or usage amount that's associated with a budget forecast, actual spend, or budget threshold. Length Constraints: Minimum length of `1`. Maximum length of `2147483647`.
budgets_budget.start_time: (Output Only) (Required) The start time of the budget limit. Format: `2017-01-01_12:00`. See [PlannedBudgetLimits](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-cost-management/latest/APIReference/API_budgets_Budget.html#awscostmanagement-Type-budgets_Budget-PlannedBudgetLimits) documentation.
budgets_budget.unit: (Output Only) The unit of measurement that's used for the budget forecast, actual spend, or budget threshold, such as USD or GBP. Length Constraints: Minimum length of `1`. Maximum length of `2147483647`.

iam_users.name_regex: (Optional) Regex string to apply to the IAM users list returned by AWS. This allows more advanced filtering not supported from the AWS API. This filtering is done locally on what AWS returns, and could have a performance impact if the result is large. Combine this with other options to narrow down the list AWS returns.
iam_users.path_prefix: (Optional) Path prefix for filtering the results. For example, the prefix `/division_abc/subdivision_xyz/` gets all users whose path starts with `/division_abc/subdivision_xyz/`. If it is not included, it defaults to a slash (`/`), listing all users. For more details, check out [list-users in the AWS CLI reference][1].
iam_users.arns: (Output Only) Set of ARNs of the matched IAM users.
iam_users.names:
(Output Only) Set of Names of the matched IAM users.

[1]: https://awscli.amazonaws.com/v2/documentation/api/latest/reference/iam/list-users.html

(Output Only) Data type of the index field. Valid values are `STRING_VALUE`, `STRING_LIST_VALUE`, `LONG_VALUE`, `DATE_VALUE`.

kendra_index.freshness: (Output Only) How "fresh" a document is. For more information, refer to [Freshness](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kendra/latest/APIReference/API_Relevance.html#Kendra-Type-Relevance-Freshness).
kendra_index.importance: (Output Only) Relative importance of the field in the search. Larger numbers provide more of a boost than smaller numbers. Minimum value of 1. Maximum value of 10.
kendra_index.rank_order: (Output Only) Determines how values should be interpreted. For more information, refer to [RankOrder](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kendra/latest/APIReference/API_Relevance.html#Kendra-Type-Relevance-RankOrder).
kendra_index.values_importance_map:
(Output Only) A list of values that should be given a different boost when they appear in the result list. For more information, refer to [ValueImportanceMap](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kendra/latest/APIReference/API_Relevance.html#Kendra-Type-Relevance-ValueImportanceMap).

A `search` block supports the following attributes:
kendra_index.displayable: (Output Only) Determines whether the field is returned in the query response. The default is `true`.
kendra_index.facetable: (Output Only) Whether the field can be used to create search facets, a count of results for each value in the field. The default is `false`.
kendra_index.searchable: (Output Only) Determines whether the field is used in the search. If the Searchable field is true, you can use relevance tuning to manually tune how Amazon Kendra weights the field in the search. The default is `true` for `string` fields and `false` for `number` and `date` fields.
kendra_index.sortable:
(Output Only) Determines whether the field can be used to sort the results of a query. If you specify sorting on a field that does not have Sortable set to true, Amazon Kendra returns an exception. The default is `false`.

There are several valid keys; for a full reference, check out [describe-db-engine-versions in the AWS CLI reference](https://awscli.amazonaws.com/v2/documentation/api/latest/reference/rds/describe-db-engine-versions.html).

If both the `version` and `preferred_versions` arguments are not configured, the data source will return the default version for the engine.

cloudfront_cache_policy.max_ttl: (Output Only) Maximum amount of time, in seconds, that objects stay in the CloudFront cache before CloudFront sends another request to the origin to see if the object has been updated.
cloudfront_cache_policy.default_ttl: (Output Only) Default amount of time, in seconds, that you want objects to stay in the CloudFront cache before CloudFront sends another request to the origin to see if the object has been updated.
cloudfront_cache_policy.comment: (Output Only) Comment to describe the cache policy.

cookies_config.cookie_behavior: (Output Only) Determines whether any cookies in viewer requests are included in the cache key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are `none`, `whitelist`, `allExcept`, `all`.
cookies_config.cookies: (Output Only) Object that contains a list of cookie names. See [Items](#items) for more information.

headers_config.header_behavior: (Output Only) Determines whether any HTTP headers are included in the cache key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are `none`, `whitelist`.
headers_config.headers: (Output Only) Object that contains a list of header names. See [Items](#items) for more information.

parameters_in_cache_key_and_forwarded_to.query_strings_config: (Output Only) Object that determines whether any URL query strings in viewer requests (and if so, which query strings) are included in the cache key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. See [Query String Config](#query-string-config) for more information.
parameters_in_cache_key_and_forwarded_to.enable_accept_encoding_brotli: (Output Only) A flag that can affect whether the Accept-Encoding HTTP header is included in the cache key and included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
parameters_in_cache_key_and_forwarded_to.enable_accept_encoding_gzip: (Output Only) A flag that can affect whether the Accept-Encoding HTTP header is included in the cache key and included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.

cloudfront_cache_policy.query_string_behavior: (Output Only) Determines whether any URL query strings in viewer requests are included in the cache key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are `none`, `whitelist`, `allExcept`, `all`.
cloudfront_cache_policy.query_strings: (Output Only) Object that contains a list of query string names. See [Items](#items) for more information.

items.items: (Output Only) List of item names (`cookies`, `headers`, or `query_strings`).

memorydb_cluster.name: (Output Only) Name of this node.
memorydb_cluster.acl_name: (Output Only) Name of the Access Control List associated with the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.auto_minor_version_upgrade: (Output Only) True when the cluster allows automatic minor version upgrades.
memorydb_cluster.address: (Output Only) DNS hostname of the node.
memorydb_cluster.port: (Output Only) Port number that this node is listening on.
memorydb_cluster.data_tiering: (Output Only) True when data tiering is enabled.
memorydb_cluster.engine_patch_version: (Output Only) Patch version number of the Redis engine used by the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.engine_version: (Output Only) Version number of the Redis engine used by the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.final_snapshot_name: (Output Only) Name of the final cluster snapshot to be created when this resource is deleted. If omitted, no final snapshot will be made.
memorydb_cluster.kms_key_arn: (Output Only) ARN of the KMS key used to encrypt the cluster at rest.
memorydb_cluster.maintenance_window: (Output Only) Weekly time range during which maintenance on the cluster is performed. Specify as a range in the format `ddd:hh24:mi-ddd:hh24:mi` (24H Clock UTC). Example: `sun:23:00-mon:01:30`.
memorydb_cluster.node_type: (Output Only) Compute and memory capacity of the nodes in the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.num_replicas_per_shard: (Output Only) The number of replicas to apply to each shard.
memorydb_cluster.num_shards: (Output Only) Number of shards in the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.parameter_group_name: (Output Only) The name of the parameter group associated with the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.security_group_ids: (Output Only) Set of VPC Security Group ID-s associated with this cluster.
memorydb_cluster.shards: (Output Only) Set of shards in this cluster.
memorydb_cluster.num_nodes: (Output Only) Number of individual nodes in this shard.
memorydb_cluster.slots: (Output Only) Keyspace for this shard. Example: `0-16383`.
memorydb_cluster.nodes: (Output Only) Set of nodes in this shard.
memorydb_cluster.availability_zone: (Output Only) The Availability Zone in which the node resides.
memorydb_cluster.create_time: (Output Only) The date and time when the node was created. Example: `2022-01-01T21:00:00Z`.
memorydb_cluster.snapshot_retention_limit: (Output Only) The number of days for which MemoryDB retains automatic snapshots before deleting them. When set to `0`, automatic backups are disabled.
memorydb_cluster.snapshot_window: (Output Only) Daily time range (in UTC) during which MemoryDB begins taking a daily snapshot of your shard. Example: `05:00-09:00`.
memorydb_cluster.sns_topic_arn: (Output Only) ARN of the SNS topic to which cluster notifications are sent.
memorydb_cluster.subnet_group_name: (Output Only) The name of the subnet group used for the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.tls_enabled: (Output Only) When true, in-transit encryption is enabled for the cluster.
memorydb_cluster.tags: (Output Only) Map of tags assigned to the cluster.

secretsmanager_secret.name: (Optional) Name of the secret to retrieve.
secretsmanager_secret.kms_key_id: (Output Only) Key Management Service (KMS) Customer Master Key (CMK) associated with the secret.
secretsmanager_secret.policy: (Output Only) Resource-based policy document that's attached to the secret.

batch_scheduling_policy.name: (Output Only) Name of the scheduling policy.
batch_scheduling_policy.tags:
(Output Only) Key-value map of resource tags

A `fairshare_policy` block supports the following arguments:
batch_scheduling_policy.compute_reservation: (Output Only) Value used to reserve some of the available maximum vCPU for fair share identifiers that have not yet been used. For more information, see [FairsharePolicy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/batch/latest/APIReference/API_FairsharePolicy.html).
batch_scheduling_policy.share_delay_seconds: (Output Only) Time period to use to calculate a fair share percentage for each fair share identifier in use, in seconds. For more information, see [FairsharePolicy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/batch/latest/APIReference/API_FairsharePolicy.html).
batch_scheduling_policy.share_identifier: (Output Only) Fair share identifier or fair share identifier prefix. For more information, see [ShareAttributes](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/batch/latest/APIReference/API_ShareAttributes.html).
batch_scheduling_policy.weight_factor: (Output Only) Weight factor for the fair share identifier. For more information, see [ShareAttributes](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/batch/latest/APIReference/API_ShareAttributes.html).

wafv2_ip_set.name: (Required) Name of the WAFv2 IP Set.
wafv2_ip_set.scope: (Required) Specifies whether this is for an AWS CloudFront distribution or for a regional application. Valid values are `CLOUDFRONT` or `REGIONAL`. To work with CloudFront, you must also specify the region `us-east-1` (N. Virginia) on the AWS provider.
wafv2_ip_set.addresses: (Output Only) An array of strings that specifies zero or more IP addresses or blocks of IP addresses in Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) notation.
wafv2_ip_set.description: (Output Only) Description of the set that helps with identification.
wafv2_ip_set.id: (Output Only) Unique identifier for the set.
wafv2_ip_set.ip_address_version: (Output Only) IP address version of the set.

filter.name: (Required) Name of the field to filter by, as defined by [the underlying AWS API](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/fsx/latest/APIReference/API_StorageVirtualMachineFilter.html).
filter.values: (Required) Set of values that are accepted for the given field. An SVM will be selected if any one of the given values matches.

fsx_ontap_storage_virtual_machine.id: (Optional) Identifier of the storage virtual machine (e.g. `svm-12345678`).

mskconnect_custom_plugin.name: (Required) Name of the custom plugin.
mskconnect_custom_plugin.arn: (Output Only) the ARN of the custom plugin.
mskconnect_custom_plugin.description: (Output Only) a summary description of the custom plugin.
mskconnect_custom_plugin.latest_revision: (Output Only) an ID of the latest successfully created revision of the custom plugin.
mskconnect_custom_plugin.state: (Output Only) the state of the custom plugin.

oam_links.arns: (Output Only) Set of ARN of the Links.

secretsmanager_secret_rotation.secret_id: (Required) Specifies the secret containing the version that you want to retrieve. You can specify either the ARN or the friendly name of the secret.
secretsmanager_secret_rotation.rotation_lambda_arn: (Output Only) Decrypted part of the protected secret information that was originally provided as a string.
secretsmanager_secret_rotation.rotation_rules: (Output Only) Decrypted part of the protected secret information that was originally provided as a binary. Base64 encoded.

ses_active_receipt_rule_set.arn: (Output Only) SES receipt rule set ARN.
ses_active_receipt_rule_set.rule_set_name: (Output Only) Name of the rule set

ssmcontacts_plan.contact_id: (Required) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the contact or escalation plan.
ssmcontacts_plan.stage: (Output Only) List of stages. A contact has an engagement plan with stages that contact specified contact channels. An escalation plan uses stages that contact specified contacts.

location_tracker_association.consumer_arn: (Required) ARN of the geofence collection associated to tracker resource.
location_tracker_association.tracker_name: (Required) Name of the tracker resource associated with a geofence collection.

route53_resolver_rules.name_regex:
(Optional) Regex string to filter resolver rule names.
  The filtering is done locally, so could have a performance impact if the result is large.
  This argument should be used along with other arguments to limit the number of results returned.
route53_resolver_rules.owner_id: (Optional) When the desired resolver rules are shared with another AWS account, the account ID of the account that the rules are shared with.
route53_resolver_rules.resolver_endpoint_id: (Optional) ID of the outbound resolver endpoint for the desired resolver rules.
route53_resolver_rules.rule_type: (Optional) Rule type of the desired resolver rules. Valid values are `FORWARD`, `SYSTEM` and `RECURSIVE`.
route53_resolver_rules.share_status: (Optional) Whether the desired resolver rules are shared and, if so, whether the current account is sharing the rules with another account, or another account is sharing the rules with the current account. Valid values are `NOT_SHARED`, `SHARED_BY_ME` or `SHARED_WITH_ME`
route53_resolver_rules.resolver_rule_ids: (Output Only) IDs of the matched resolver rules.

cloudfront_origin_access_identities.comments: (Optional) Filter origin access identities by comment.
cloudfront_origin_access_identities.iam_arns: (Output Only) Set of ARNs of the matched origin access identities.
cloudfront_origin_access_identities.ids: (Output Only) Set of ids of the matched origin access identities.
cloudfront_origin_access_identities.s3_canonical_user_ids: (Output Only) Set of S3 canonical user IDs of the matched origin access identities.

ecrpublic_authorization_token.authorization_token: (Output Only) Temporary IAM authentication credentials to access the ECR repository encoded in base64 in the form of `user_name:password`.
ecrpublic_authorization_token.expires_at: (Output Only) Time in UTC RFC3339 format when the authorization token expires.

ecrpublic_authorization_token.password: (Output Only) Password decoded from the authorization token.
ecrpublic_authorization_token.user_name: (Output Only) User name decoded from the authorization token.

ebs_volume.most_recent:
(Optional) If more than one result is returned, use the most
recent Volume.
ebs_volume.filter:

several valid keys, for a full reference, check out

ebs_volume.encrypted: (Output Only) Whether the disk is encrypted.

redshift_subnet_group.name: (Required) Name of the cluster subnet group for which information is requested.

redshift_subnet_group.description: (Output Only) Description of the Redshift Subnet group.

vpc_endpoint_service.service: (Optional) Common name of an AWS service (e.g., `s3`).

For AWS services the service name is usually in the form `com.amazonaws.<region>.<service>` (the SageMaker Notebook service is an exception to this rule, the service name is in the form `aws.sagemaker.<region>.notebook`).
vpc_endpoint_service.tags: (Output Only) Map of tags assigned to the resource.

vpc_endpoint_service.values: (Required) Set of values that are accepted for the given filter field. Results will be selected if any given value matches.
vpc_endpoint_service.acceptance_required: (Output Only) Whether or not VPC endpoint connection requests to the service must be accepted by the service owner - `true` or `false`.
vpc_endpoint_service.arn: (Output Only) ARN of the VPC endpoint service.
vpc_endpoint_service.availability_zones: (Output Only) Availability Zones in which the service is available.
vpc_endpoint_service.base_endpoint_dns_names: (Output Only) The DNS names for the service.
vpc_endpoint_service.manages_vpc_endpoints: (Output Only) Whether or not the service manages its VPC endpoints - `true` or `false`.
vpc_endpoint_service.owner: (Output Only) AWS account ID of the service owner or `amazon`.
vpc_endpoint_service.private_dns_name: (Output Only) Private DNS name for the service.
vpc_endpoint_service.service_id: (Output Only) ID of the endpoint service.
vpc_endpoint_service.supported_ip_address_types: (Output Only) The supported IP address types.
vpc_endpoint_service.vpc_endpoint_policy_supported: (Output Only) Whether or not the service supports endpoint policies - `true` or `false`.

servicecatalog_product.id:

service_discovery_http_namespace.tags: (Output Only) Map of tags for the resource.

dms_certificate.certificate_id: (Required) A customer-assigned name for the certificate. Identifiers must begin with a letter and must contain only ASCII letters, digits, and hyphens. They can't end with a hyphen or contain two consecutive hyphens.
dms_certificate.certificate_creation_date: (Output Only) The date that the certificate was created.

dms_certificate.certificate_owner: (Output Only) The owner of the certificate.
dms_certificate.certificate_arn: (Output Only) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) for the certificate.
dms_certificate.certificate_wallet: (Output Only) The owner of the certificate.
dms_certificate.key_length: (Output Only) The key length of the cryptographic algorithm being used.
dms_certificate.signing_algorithm: (Output Only) The algorithm for the certificate.
dms_certificate.valid_from_date: (Output Only) The beginning date that the certificate is valid.
dms_certificate.valid_to_date: (Output Only) The final date that the certificate is valid.

batch_job_queue.name: (Required) Name of the job queue.
batch_job_queue.arn: (Output Only) ARN of the job queue.
batch_job_queue.scheduling_policy_arn: (Output Only) The ARN of the fair share scheduling policy. If this attribute has a value, the job queue uses a fair share scheduling policy. If this attribute does not have a value, the job queue uses a first in, first out (FIFO) scheduling policy.
batch_job_queue.status: (Output Only) Current status of the job queue (for example, `CREATING` or `VALID`).
batch_job_queue.status_reason:
(Output Only) Short, human-readable string to provide additional details about the current status
    of the job queue.
batch_job_queue.state: (Output Only) Describes the ability of the queue to accept new jobs (for example, `ENABLED` or `DISABLED`).
batch_job_queue.tags: (Output Only) Key-value map of resource tags
batch_job_queue.priority:
(Output Only) Priority of the job queue. Job queues with a higher priority are evaluated first when
    associated with the same compute environment.
batch_job_queue.compute_environment_order:
(Output Only) The compute environments that are attached to the job queue and the order in
    which job placement is preferred. Compute environments are selected for job placement in ascending order.

auditmanager_control.name: (Required) Name of the control.
auditmanager_control.type: (Required) Type of control. Valid values are `Custom` and `Standard`.

fsx_windows_file_system.id: (Output Only) Identifier of the file system (e.g. `fs-12345678`).
fsx_windows_file_system.active_directory_id: (Output Only) The ID for Microsoft Active Directory instance that the file system is join to.
fsx_windows_file_system.aliases: (Output Only) An array DNS alias names associated with the Amazon FSx file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.arn: (Output Only) Amazon Resource Name of the file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.audit_log_configuration: (Output Only) The configuration that Amazon FSx for Windows File Server uses to audit and log user accesses of files, folders, and file shares on the Amazon FSx for Windows File Server file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.automatic_backup_retention_days: (Output Only) The number of days to retain automatic backups.
fsx_windows_file_system.copy_tags_to_backups: (Output Only) A boolean flag indicating whether tags on the file system should be copied to backups.
fsx_windows_file_system.daily_automatic_backup_start_time: (Output Only) The preferred time (in `HH:MM` format) to take daily automatic backups, in the UTC time zone.
fsx_windows_file_system.deployment_type: (Output Only) The file system deployment type.
fsx_windows_file_system.disk_iops_configuration: (Output Only) The SSD IOPS configuration for the file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.dns_name: (Output Only) DNS name for the file system (e.g. `fs-12345678.corp.example.com`).
fsx_windows_file_system.kms_key_id: (Output Only) ARN for the KMS Key to encrypt the file system at rest.
fsx_windows_file_system.owner_id: (Output Only) AWS account identifier that created the file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.preferred_subnet_id: (Output Only) Specifies the subnet in which you want the preferred file server to be located.
fsx_windows_file_system.preferred_file_server_ip: (Output Only) The IP address of the primary, or preferred, file server.
fsx_windows_file_system.storage_capacity: (Output Only) The storage capacity of the file system in gibibytes (GiB).
fsx_windows_file_system.storage_type: (Output Only) The type of storage the file system is using. If set to `SSD`, the file system uses solid state drive storage. If set to `HDD`, the file system uses hard disk drive storage.
fsx_windows_file_system.subnet_ids: (Output Only) Specifies the IDs of the subnets that the file system is accessible from.
fsx_windows_file_system.tags: (Output Only) The tags to associate with the file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.throughput_capacity: (Output Only) Throughput (megabytes per second) of the file system in power of 2 increments. Minimum of `8` and maximum of `2048`.
fsx_windows_file_system.vpc_id: (Output Only) The ID of the primary virtual private cloud (VPC) for the file system.
fsx_windows_file_system.weekly_maintenance_start_time: (Output Only) The preferred start time (in `d:HH:MM` format) to perform weekly maintenance, in the UTC time zone.

cloudcontrolapi_resource.identifier: (Required) Identifier of the CloudFormation resource type. For example, `vpc-12345678`.

(Required) CloudFormation resource type name. For example, `AWS::EC2::VPC`.

The following arguments are optional:

Underlying attributes can be referenced via the [`jsondecode()` function](https://www.terraform.io/docs/language/functions/jsondecode.html), for example, `jsondecode(data.aws_cloudcontrolapi_resource.example.properties)["example"]`.

lex_slot_type.name: (Output Only) Name of the slot type. The name is not case sensitive.
lex_slot_type.version: (Output Only) Version of the slot type.
lex_slot_type.checksum:
(Output Only) Checksum identifying the version of the slot type that was created. The checksum is
not included as an argument because the resource will add it automatically when updating the slot type.
lex_slot_type.created_date: (Output Only) Date when the slot type version was created.
lex_slot_type.description: (Output Only) Description of the slot type.
lex_slot_type.enumeration_value:
(Output Only) Set of EnumerationValue objects that defines the values that
the slot type can take. Each value can have a set of synonyms, which are additional values that help
train the machine learning model about the values that it resolves for a slot.
lex_slot_type.last_updated_date: (Output Only) Date when the $LATEST version of this slot type was updated.
lex_slot_type.value_selection_strategy:
(Output Only) Determines the slot resolution strategy that Amazon Lex
uses to return slot type values. `ORIGINAL_VALUE` returns the value entered by the user if the user
value is similar to the slot value. `TOP_RESOLUTION` returns the first value in the resolution list
if there is a resolution list for the slot, otherwise null is returned.

s3_object.checksum_mode: (Optional) To retrieve the object's checksum, this argument must be `ENABLED`. If you enable `checksum_mode` and the object is encrypted with KMS, you must have permission to use the `kms:Decrypt` action. Valid values: `ENABLED`
s3_object.key: (Required) Full path to the object inside the bucket
s3_object.version_id: (Output Only) Latest version ID of the object returned.
s3_object.body: (Output Only) Object data (see limitations above to understand cases in which this field is actually available)
s3_object.bucket_key_enabled: (Output Only) (Optional) Whether or not to use [Amazon S3 Bucket Keys](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/bucket-key.html) for SSE-KMS.
s3_object.cache_control: (Output Only) Caching behavior along the request/reply chain.
s3_object.checksum_crc32: (Output Only) The base64-encoded, 32-bit CRC32 checksum of the object.
s3_object.checksum_crc32c: (Output Only) The base64-encoded, 32-bit CRC32C checksum of the object.
s3_object.checksum_sha1: (Output Only) The base64-encoded, 160-bit SHA-1 digest of the object.
s3_object.checksum_sha256: (Output Only) The base64-encoded, 256-bit SHA-256 digest of the object.
s3_object.content_disposition: (Output Only) Presentational information for the object.
s3_object.content_encoding: (Output Only) What content encodings have been applied to the object and thus what decoding mechanisms must be applied to obtain the media-type referenced by the Content-Type header field.
s3_object.content_language: (Output Only) Language the content is in.
s3_object.content_length: (Output Only) Size of the body in bytes.
s3_object.content_type: (Output Only) Standard MIME type describing the format of the object data.
s3_object.etag: (Output Only) [ETag](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_ETag) generated for the object (an MD5 sum of the object content in case it's not encrypted)
s3_object.expiration: (Output Only) If the object expiration is configured (see [object lifecycle management](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/object-lifecycle-mgmt.html)), the field includes this header. It includes the expiry-date and rule-id key value pairs providing object expiration information. The value of the rule-id is URL encoded.
s3_object.expires: (Output Only) Date and time at which the object is no longer cacheable.
s3_object.last_modified: (Output Only) Last modified date of the object in RFC1123 format (e.g., `Mon, 02 Jan 2006 15:04:05 MST`)
s3_object.metadata: (Output Only) Map of metadata stored with the object in S3. [Keys](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions/types#maps-objects) are always returned in lowercase.
s3_object.object_lock_legal_hold_status: (Output Only) Indicates whether this object has an active [legal hold](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/object-lock-overview.html#object-lock-legal-holds). This field is only returned if you have permission to view an object's legal hold status.
s3_object.object_lock_mode: (Output Only) Object lock [retention mode](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/object-lock-overview.html#object-lock-retention-modes) currently in place for this object.
s3_object.object_lock_retain_until_date: (Output Only) The date and time when this object's object lock will expire.
s3_object.server_side_encryption: (Output Only) If the object is stored using server-side encryption (KMS or Amazon S3-managed encryption key), this field includes the chosen encryption and algorithm used.
s3_object.sse_kms_key_id: (Output Only) If present, specifies the ID of the Key Management Service (KMS) master encryption key that was used for the object.
s3_object.storage_class: (Output Only) [Storage class](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/storage-class-intro.html) information of the object. Available for all objects except for `Standard` storage class objects.
s3_object.website_redirect_location: (Output Only) If the bucket is configured as a website, redirects requests for this object to another object in the same bucket or to an external URL. Amazon S3 stores the value of this header in the object metadata.
s3_object.tags:
(Output Only) - Map of tags assigned to the object.

-> Note: Terraform ignores all leading `/`s in the object's `key` and treats multiple `/`s in the rest of the object's `key` as a single `/`, so values of `/index.html` and `index.html` correspond to the same S3 object as do `first//second///third//` and `first/second/third/`.

redshift_cluster_credentials.auto_create: (Optional)  Create a database user with the name specified for the user named in `db_user` if one does not exist.
redshift_cluster_credentials.cluster_identifier: (Required) Unique identifier of the cluster that contains the database for which your are requesting credentials.
redshift_cluster_credentials.db_name: (Optional) Name of a database that DbUser is authorized to log on to. If `db_name` is not specified, `db_user` can log on to any existing database.
redshift_cluster_credentials.db_user: (Required) Name of a database user. If a user name matching `db_user` exists in the database, the temporary user credentials have the same permissions as the  existing user. If `db_user` doesn't exist in the database and `auto_create` is `True`, a new user is created using the value for `db_user` with `PUBLIC` permissions.  If a database user matching the value for `db_user` doesn't exist and `not` is `False`, then the command succeeds but the connection attempt will fail because the user doesn't exist in the database.
redshift_cluster_credentials.db_groups: (Optional) List of the names of existing database groups that the user named in `db_user` will join for the current session, in addition to any group memberships for an existing user. If not specified, a new user is added only to `PUBLIC`.
redshift_cluster_credentials.duration_seconds: (Optional) The number of seconds until the returned temporary password expires. Valid values are between `900` and `3600`. Default value is `900`.
redshift_cluster_credentials.db_password: (Output Only) Temporary password that authorizes the user name returned by `db_user` to log on to the database `db_name`.
redshift_cluster_credentials.expiration: (Output Only) Date and time the password in `db_password` expires.

The following arguments are optional:

(Optional) A string that identifies one or more attributes to retrieve from the table. These attributes can include scalars, sets, or elements of a JSON document. The attributes in the expression must be separated by commas.
If no attribute names are specified, then all attributes are returned. If any of the requested attributes are not found, they do not appear in the result.

action.association_method: (Required) Defines how a segment is mapped. Values can be `constant` or `tag`. `constant` statically defines the segment to associate the attachment to. `tag` uses the value of a tag to dynamically try to map to a segment.reference_policies_elements_condition_operators.html) to evaluate.
action.segment: (Optional) Name of the `segment` to share as defined in the `segments` section. This is used only when the `association_method` is `constant`.
action.tag_value_of_key: (Optional) Maps the attachment to the value of a known key. This is used with the `association_method` is `tag`. For example a `tag` of `stage = test`, will map to a segment named `test`. The value must exactly match the name of a segment. This allows you to have many segments, but use only a single rule without having to define multiple nearly identical conditions. This prevents creating many similar conditions that all use the same keys to map to segments.
action.require_acceptance: (Optional) Determines if this mapping should override the segment value for `require_attachment_acceptance`. You can only set this to `true`, indicating that this setting applies only to segments that have `require_attachment_acceptance` set to `false`. If the segment already has the default `require_attachment_acceptance`, you can set this to inherit segments acceptance value.

attachment_policies.description: (Optional) A user-defined description that further helps identify the rule.
attachment_policies.rule_number: (Required) An integer from `1` to `65535` indicating the rule's order number. Rules are processed in order from the lowest numbered rule to the highest. Rules stop processing when a rule is matched. It's important to make sure that you number your rules in the exact order that you want them processed.

core_network_configuration.asn_ranges: (Required) List of strings containing Autonomous System Numbers (ASNs) to assign to Core Network Edges. By default, the core network automatically assigns an ASN for each Core Network Edge but you can optionally define the ASN in the edge-locations for each Region. The ASN uses an array of integer ranges only from `64512` to `65534` and `4200000000` to `4294967294` expressed as a string like `"64512-65534"`. No other ASN ranges can be used.
core_network_configuration.inside_cidr_blocks: (Optional) The Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) block range used to create tunnels for AWS Transit Gateway Connect. The format is standard AWS CIDR range (for example, `10.0.1.0/24`). You can optionally define the inside CIDR in the Core Network Edges section per Region. The minimum is a `/24` for IPv4 or `/64` for IPv6. You can provide multiple `/24` subnets or a larger CIDR range. If you define a larger CIDR range, new Core Network Edges will be automatically assigned `/24` and `/64` subnets from the larger CIDR. an Inside CIDR block is required for attaching Connect attachments to a Core Network Edge.
core_network_configuration.vpn_ecmp_support: (Optional) Indicates whether the core network forwards traffic over multiple equal-cost routes using VPN. The value can be either `true` or `false`. The default is `true`.

edge_locations.locations: (Required) An AWS Region code, such as `us-east-1`.
edge_locations.asn: (Optional) ASN of the Core Network Edge in an AWS Region. By default, the ASN will be a single integer automatically assigned from `asn_ranges`
edge_locations.inside_cidr_blocks: (Optional) The local CIDR blocks for this Core Network Edge for AWS Transit Gateway Connect attachments. By default, this CIDR block will be one or more optional IPv4 and IPv6 CIDR prefixes auto-assigned from `inside_cidr_blocks`.

segments.allow_filter: (Optional)  List of strings of segment names that explicitly allows only routes from the segments that are listed in the array. Use the `allow_filter` setting if a segment has a well-defined group of other segments that connectivity should be restricted to. It is applied after routes have been shared in `segment_actions`. If a segment is listed in `allow_filter`, attachments between the two segments will have routes if they are also shared in the segment-actions area. For example, you might have a segment named "video-producer" that should only ever share routes with a "video-distributor" segment, no matter how many other share statements are created.
segments.deny_filter: (Optional) An array of segments that disallows routes from the segments listed in the array. It is applied only after routes have been shared in `segment_actions`. If a segment is listed in the `deny_filter`, attachments between the two segments will never have routes shared across them. For example, you might have a "financial" payment segment that should never share routes with a "development" segment, regardless of how many other share statements are created. Adding the payments segment to the deny-filter parameter prevents any shared routes from being created with other segments.
segments.description: (Optional) A user-defined string describing the segment.
segments.edge_locations: (Optional) A list of strings of AWS Region names. Allows you to define a more restrictive set of Regions for a segment. The edge location must be a subset of the locations that are defined for `edge_locations` in the `core_network_configuration`.
segments.isolate_attachments: (Optional) This Boolean setting determines whether attachments on the same segment can communicate with each other. If set to `true`, the only routes available will be either shared routes through the share actions, which are attachments in other segments, or static routes. The default value is `false`. For example, you might have a segment dedicated to "development" that should never allow VPCs to talk to each other, even if theyre on the same segment. In this example, you would keep the default parameter of `false`.
segments.name: (Required) Unique name for a segment. The name is a string used in other parts of the policy document, as well as in the console for metrics and other reference points. Valid characters are a-z, and 0-9.
segments.require_attachment_acceptance: (Optional) This Boolean setting determines whether attachment requests are automatically approved or require acceptance. The default is `true`, indicating that attachment requests require acceptance. For example, you might use this setting to allow a "sandbox" segment to allow any attachment request so that a core network or attachment administrator does not need to review and approve attachment requests. In this example, `require_attachment_acceptance` is set to `false`.

segment_actions.action: (Required) Action to take for the chosen segment. Valid values `create-route` or `share`.
segment_actions.description: (Optional) A user-defined string describing the segment action.
segment_actions.destination_cidr_blocks: (Optional) List of strings containing CIDRs. You can define the IPv4 and IPv6 CIDR notation for each AWS Region. For example, `10.1.0.0/16` or `2001:db8::/56`. This is an array of CIDR notation strings.
segment_actions.destinations: (Optional) A list of strings. Valid values include `["blackhole"]` or a list of attachment ids.
segment_actions.mode: (Optional) String. This mode places the attachment and return routes in each of the `share_with` segments. Valid values include: `attachment-route`.
segment_actions.share_with: (Optional) A list of strings to share with. Must be a substring is all segments. Valid values include: `["
segment_actions.share_with_except: (Optional) A set subtraction of segments to not share with.

edge_locations.locations: (Required) An AWS Region code, such as `us-east-1`.
edge_locations.asn: (Optional) ASN of the Core Network Edge in an AWS Region. By default, the ASN will be a single integer automatically assigned from `asn_ranges`
edge_locations.inside_cidr_blocks: (Optional) The local CIDR blocks for this Core Network Edge for AWS Transit Gateway Connect attachments. By default, this CIDR block will be one or more optional IPv4 and IPv6 CIDR prefixes auto-assigned from `inside_cidr_blocks`.

(Optional) Creates a unique name beginning with the specified
  prefix. Conflicts with `name`.

(Required) The contents of the public key certificate in
  PEM-encoded format.
